    "output": "To combine two separate subtitle files (main.srt and comments.srt) into one subtitle track and embed it into recording.mov, you first need to merge the subtitles into a single subtitle file. Since ffmpeg does not directly support merging subtitle files, you can concatenate them manually or using scripting before embedding.\n\nHere is a step-by-step approach:\n\n1. **Merge Subtitle Files:**\n   - You can merge SRT files by adjusting the timecodes of the second subtitle (comments.srt) to appear after the first (main.srt).\n   - This requires knowing the duration of main.srt subtitles or the video duration to offset the comments.srt timestamps appropriately.\n   - Alternatively, you can merge subtitles by concatenating them with adjusted timecodes using subtitle processing tools or scripts.\n\n2. **Embed the Merged Subtitle Track:**\n   - After preparing a single combined `merged.srt` file, embed it as a subtitle track into the input video `recording.mov`.\n   - Use the `-c:s mov_text` codec (for MP4/MOV compatible subtitles).\n   - Use `-map` options to map the video, audio, and subtitle streams correctly.\n\n**Assuming you've created `merged.srt` with combined subtitles properly synchronized, hereâ€™s the ffmpeg command to embed it:**\n\n```bash\nffmpeg -i recording.mov -i merged.srt -c:v copy -c:a copy -c:s mov_text -map 0:v -map 0:a -map 1 -metadata:s:s:0 language=eng output.mov\n```\n\n**Explanation:**\n- `-i recording.mov` loads the video with audio streams.\n- `-i merged.srt` loads the merged subtitle file.\n- `-c:v copy -c:a copy` copies existing video and audio without re-encoding.\n- `-c:s mov_text` encodes subtitles in a format compatible with MOV containers.\n- `-map 0:v -map 0:a` selects the original video and audio streams.\n- `-map 1` selects the subtitle track from `merged.srt`.\n- `-metadata:s:s:0 language=eng` sets the subtitle language tag to English.\n- `output.mov` is the output file with embedded combined subtitles.\n\n---\n\n**If you need assistance merging the SRTs before embedding, please specify, and I can help create an adjusted combined subtitle file.**",
